{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657146","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657146"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:25:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:25:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19122"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19122","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19122"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11856"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81876"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11856","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11856"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19122"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67153"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"763"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"7415"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27819"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27902"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27930"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81876","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81876"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents with a reducible swelling in his right groin that becomes more prominent when standing or coughing. During examination, the clinician is attempting to determine if this is a direct or indirect inguinal hernia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECertain landmarks can be used to help distinguish a direct from an indirect inguinal hernia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following anatomical structures most useful in making this distinction?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Conjoint tendon","External inguinal ring","Inferior epigastric vessels","Inguinal ligament","Pubic tubercle"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn reality, there is little practical or clinical value in being able to distinguish between a direct and indirect inguinal hernia. It is more important - on clinical assessment - to be able to diagnose and differentiate an inguinal hernia from other causes of groin swellings, such as enlarged lymph nodes. The \u003Cstrong\u003Einferior epigastric vessels\u003C/strong\u003E serve as the critical anatomical landmark for distinguishing between direct and indirect inguinal hernias. Indirect hernias protrude lateral to these vessels through the deep inguinal ring, while direct hernias emerge medial to them through Hesselbach\u0027s triangle. It is unlikely that the inferior epigastric vessels will be apparent in many individuals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInguinal ligament\u003C/strong\u003E forms the floor of the inguinal canal but does not help distinguish between hernia types\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPubic tubercle\u003C/strong\u003E serves as a landmark for the external inguinal ring but does not differentiate hernia types\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConjoint tendon\u003C/strong\u003E forms part of the posterior wall of the inguinal canal but is not useful for determining hernia type\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExternal inguinal ring\u003C/strong\u003E is the exit point for both types of hernias and cannot differentiate between them\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding this anatomical relationship is important for surgical planning as the approach may differ depending on whether the hernia is direct or indirect.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The deep inguinal ring is located lateral to the inferior epigastric vessels in the transversalis fascia.","The deep inguinal ring is positioned halfway between the anterior superior iliac spine and the pubic tubercle.","Direct inguinal hernias protrude medial to the inferior epigastric vessels through Hesselbach\u0027s triangle."],"references":["Jamadar et al. Sonography of Inguinal Region Hernias, Gastrointestinal Imaging, 2006, https://ajronline.org/doi/10.2214/AJR.05.1813"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67153"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19122"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67153","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67153"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-27T10:28:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-27T10:29:23+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11856"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81876"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"}